  <bioghist id="aspace_69087ebfac8dee6766a0a60f37cf3f48">
    <head>History</head>
<p>The Voegtly Evangelical Church is a German-language Protestant Church Established in 1833 by Swiss immigrants to Allegheny City (presently North Side, Pittsburgh, Pa.). Named for Nicholas Voegtly, Sr. who donated the land as a site for the first (one story) brick church in 1833. Known in former times as the German United Evangelical Protestant Church, Allegheny, Pa., and later as Pilgram Evangelical Church.</p>  </bioghist>
  <scopecontent id="aspace_26dd8ddc37485f3854af9747bd19cf64">
    <head>Scope and Content Notes</head>
<p>The Records of Voegtly Evangelical Church contain church history; 100th anniversary booklet; church bulletins; church registers, including deaths, marriages, baptisms, and confirmations; and Cemetary records including inserts; Reel 3 includes additional cemetery grave records that were filmed by the Western Pennsylvania Genealogical Society in 1986. They have been assigned 85:11, Reel 3, designation to keep them in close proximity to the records microfilmed earlier. These records give names, age, grave location (block. lot); in addition one may find lists of children's graves, and notes on internments.</p><p>NOTE: Records up unitl 1910 are in German and some registers contain lists of names.</p>  </scopecontent>
